On the National Day for the Victims of Communism, the statement honors the memory of over 100 million people who have been killed and persecuted by communist totalitarian regimes. It reaffirms support for those striving for peace, prosperity, and freedom worldwide. The statement highlights the negative effects of communism, including repression, death, and the subordination of human rights. It mentions specific atrocities such as the Holodomor, the Great Terror, and the killing fields of Cambodia. The statement concludes by remembering those who have been denied life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness under communist regimes and pledging to continue advancing freedom and opportunity for all.